Preheat the #oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{2}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Roughly chop the @walnuts{20%g}.

Place a large pan over medium heat (no oil).

Once hot, dry-fry the walnuts, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%mins}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to a medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%g} and onion. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Fry until chicken is golden brown and cooked through, ~{8-10%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging we use to keep it fresh.

While the chicken cooks, pop the @flatbread base{2} onto a #baking tray{}.

Bake until warm and starting to turn golden, ~{10-12%mins}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, trim the @salad leaves{120%g}, halve lengthways and thinly slice widthways.

Cut the @tomato{2}(cut into 1cm chunks) into 1cm chunks.

In a #medium bowl{}, mix together the @red wine vinegar{1%sachet}, @oil{1%tbsp}, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Mix well to combine.

Just before serving, toss the salad leaves, tomato and walnuts through the dressing.

When the chicken is cooked, reduce the heat to medium.

Stir the @Rogan Josh curry paste{1%sachet} into the pan along with @water{50%ml}(double for 4p).

Simmer until thickened and slightly reduced, ~{3-4%mins}.

Once simmered, add @sugar{1/2%tsp}, @butter{1%tbsp}(double for 4p) and the @honey{1%sachet} to the pan. Stir until the butter is melted.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Transfer the flatbread bases to your plates.

Scatter over the tomato salad.

Load on the curried chicken and onion.

Finish with a drizzle of @sweet chilli sauce{1%sachet} and a sprinkling of @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet}(use less if you don't like spice).